LEARNING_OUTCOMES:
After completing the course the student:
   - understands the difference between private and public law, understands the place of civil law in the private law system and knows the internal structure of civil law;
   - knows the sources of civil law and can navigate the first and third parts of the Civil Code when solving legal problems;
   - understands the content of the basic principles of civil law and their relevance to the application of civil law;
   - understands the basic concepts relating to the status of private law persons (legal personality, legal capacity, tort capacity) and can describe their creation, termination and limitation;
   - understands the concept of a juridical act, can distinguish it from other legal facts, can describe and apply the basic methods of interpretation of juridical acts, understands the differences between the various types of defects of a juridical act and can identify in which cases a juridical act is affected by such defects;
   - understands the nature of direct representation and can distinguish between its types;
   - understands the rules for calculating time in  law and the difference between limitation, prescription and extinction of a right by lapse of time;
   - can explain the concept of a thing in the legal sense, the parts of a thing and accessories and understands the nature of the basic typologies of things, in particular the difference between tangible and intangible things and movable and immovable things;
   - understands the system of absolute property rights and the general characteristics of such rights (erga omnes effects, numerus clausus, etc.);
   - can describe the content of ownership and the mechanism of its protection and the basic nature of co-ownership relations;
   - can interpret the prerequisites of succession and distinguish the basic features of the various titles of succession.

